Types of Loss Functions

Loss Function means:

"How much error the model made."

Smaller loss = Better prediction

1️⃣ Probabilistic Losses

Used when:

Model predicts probabilities

Mostly used in:

Classification problems

Examples:

Digit recognition
Cat vs Dog
Spam detection

============================

Common Probabilistic Losses

| Loss Function            | Used For         |
| ------------------------ | ---------------- |
| Binary Crossentropy      | 2 classes        |
| Categorical Crossentropy | Multiple classes |


Example

Actual digit = 5

Prediction:

| Digit | Probability |
| ----- | ----------- |
| 5     | 0.95        |

Very good prediction → Low loss

If:

| Digit | Probability |
| ----- | ----------- |
| 2     | 0.90        |

Wrong prediction → High loss
Real-time Example

Like:

Weather app predicting rain probability.


==================

2️⃣ Regression Losses

Used when:

Predicting continuous numbers

Examples:

House price
Temperature
Stock price


Common Regression Losses
-----------------------

| Loss Function | Meaning                 |
| ------------- | ----------------------- |
| MAE           | Mean Absolute Error     |
| MSE           | Mean Squared Error      |
| RMSE          | Root Mean Squared Error |

===============

MSE (Most Common)

Measures:

Average squared error

-----------------
Example

Actual price = ₹10 lakh
Predicted = ₹9 lakh

Error = ₹1 lakh

Loss calculates this error mathematically.

Real-time Example

Like:

Difference between estimated budget and actual expense.

=========================

3️⃣ Hinge Losses ("Maximum-Margin" Classification)

Used mainly in:

Support Vector Machines (SVM)

Goal:

Separate classes with maximum distance.

Idea

Correct predictions:

Small loss

Wrong predictions:

Large loss

Hinge Loss Formula

Hinge Loss=max(0,1−y⋅f(x))

Where:

y = actual label
f(x) = prediction

Real-time Example

Like:

Keeping two teams separated with a safety gap.

